Welcome to the "Terminal State" rabbit hole. What you’re seeing isn't actually a bug—it’s a classic case of conflicting signals.

Here is what’s happening: Ghostty, Neovim, and Yazi are all trying to "drive" the cursor. When you enter an app like Neovim, it sends an escape sequence to the terminal saying, "Hey, I'm an editor, change the cursor to a block so the user can see where they are." When you exit, the app should tell the terminal to go back to its default... but it often fails or resets it to the "system default" (a block) instead of your "Ghostty preference" (the thin line).

Here is how to fix it and force Ghostty to keep that sleek thin line.

1. The Ghostty Fix (The "Force" Method)
You can tell Ghostty to be more "stubborn" about its cursor style in your ~/.config/ghostty/config. Add or update these lines:

Bash
# Sets your preferred default
cursor-style = bar
# Optional: makes it blink if you like that
cursor-style-blink = true
2. The Neovim Fix
Neovim is notorious for resetting the cursor to a block on exit. You can add this to your init.lua to ensure it "hands back" the thin bar when you quit:

Lua
-- Force a thin bar (guaranteed) on exit
vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd("VimLeave", {
  callback = function()
    io.write("\27[6 q") -- The ANSI escape code for a steady bar
  end,
})
3. The "Shell Reset" (The Fail-Safe)
If it still happens after exiting Yazi or other CLI tools, you can add a "reset" to your shell prompt. If you use zsh (common on Arch), add this to your .zshrc:

Bash
# This sends the "make cursor a bar" sequence every time the prompt draws
_fix_cursor() {
   echo -ne '\e[6 q'
}
precmd_functions+=(_fix_cursor)
Why is this happening in Ghostty and not Alacritty?
Alacritty is often configured with a "fixed" cursor that ignores certain escape sequences, or your Alacritty config might have been set to block already, so you never noticed the change. Ghostty is more compliant with modern terminal standards—it actually listens when an app says "Change the cursor!" Unfortunately, many apps are "polite" enough to change it upon entry, but too "lazy" to change it back upon exit.

