1. The Config Syntax Trap
Ghostty is very picky about its syntax. It uses equals signs (=) but no quotes for strings, and it strictly uses dashes (-), not underscores.

Your input: cursor_style = hollow-block (Uses underscore)

Correct syntax: cursor-style = hollow-block (Uses dash)

Also, title in Ghostty usually refers to the initial window title, but many shells (and Hyprland) override this immediately with the current directory or process name.

Try this exact block in ~/.config/ghostty/config:

Bash
# No quotes needed!
title = thunderghost
cursor-style = bar
cursor-style-blink = false

# Add some padding so it doesn't look cramped
window-padding-x = 10
window-padding-y = 10
Note: Ghostty doesn't always live-reload every single setting (like title). Close all Ghostty instances (pkill ghostty) and restart it to be sure.

2. The Bash Cursor Fix
Since you're using Bash, we can't use precmd_functions like in Zsh. Instead, we hook into the PROMPT_COMMAND. This ensures that every time your prompt (the $ or user@host) reappears after an app closes, the cursor is forced back to a bar.

Add this to the bottom of your ~/.bashrc:

Bash
# Force cursor to a thin bar (6) whenever the prompt is drawn
# \e[6 q = steady bar
# \e[5 q = blinking bar
PROMPT_COMMAND='echo -ne "\e[6 q"; '$PROMPT_COMMAND
