To get your font and title exactly where you want them, we need to adjust the Ghostty config and likely "silence" your Bash prompt, as it’s almost certainly the culprit behind the title resets.

1. Changing the Font Size
In Ghostty, the font size is handled by the font-size directive. Unlike Alacritty, which sometimes uses floats, Ghostty prefers integers or simple decimals.

Add this to your ~/.config/ghostty/config:

Bash
font-size = 14
# You can also specify the font family here if you haven't
font-family = "FiraCode Nerd Font" 
2. Fixing the "Persistent" Title
The reason your title = thunderghost keeps disappearing is that your ~/.bashrc (or the system-wide /etc/bash.bashrc) contains a function that sends a "set title" escape sequence every time the prompt appears. It essentially says: "I don't care what the terminal config says, the title is now [user@host:dir]."

Option A: The "Ghostty Way" (Ignore the Shell)
You can tell Ghostty to simply ignore requests from the shell to change the title. Add this to your Ghostty config:

Bash
shell-integration-features = no-title
Note: This will keep the title as "thunderghost" permanently, but it means you won't see the current directory in the title bar anymore.

Option B: The "Bash Way" (Manual Control)
If you want to allow the title to change but set it manually from your script, you can add this to your ~/.bashrc:

Bash
# This function sets the terminal title
set_title() {
    echo -ne "\033]0;$1\007"
}

# Run it immediately
set_title "thunderghost"
3. Your Updated "Thunderghost" Config
Here is the refined version of your config with the new settings integrated:

Bash
# Branding
title = thunderghost

# Font Settings
font-size = 14
# font-family = "Your Preferred Font"

# Cursor Fixes
cursor-style = bar
cursor-style-blink = false

# Layout & Behavior
window-padding-x = 10
window-padding-y = 10

# The "Control" Switches
# 'no-cursor' stops the block jump
# 'no-title' stops the shell from overwriting your title
shell-integration-features = no-cursor,no-title
